SIMPLE: savor
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Savor
<hw>Sa"vor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>savour</ets>,
<ets>savor</ets>, <ets>savur</ets>, OF. <ets>savor</ets>,
<ets>savour</ets>, F. <ets>saveur</ets>, fr. L. <ets>sapor</ets>, fr.
<ets>sapere</ets> to taste, savor. See <er>Sage</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and
cf. <er>Sapid</er>, <er>Insipid</er>, <er>Sapor</er>.]</ety>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>savour</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That
property of a thing which affects the organs of taste or smell; taste
and odor; flavor; relish; scent; <as>as, the <ex>savor</ex> of an orange
or a rose; an ill <ex>savor</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I smell sweet <qex>savors</qex> and I feel soft things.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, specific flavor or quality; characteristic
property; distinctive temper, tinge, taint, and the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why is not my life a continual joy, and the <qex>savor</qex> of
heaven perpetually upon my spirit?</q> <rj><qau>Baxter.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Sense of smell; power to scent, or trace by
scent.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Beyond my <xex>savor</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Herbert.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Pleasure; delight; attractiveness.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She shall no <qex>savor</qex> have therein but lite.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Taste; flavor; relish; odor; scent;
smell.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Savor</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Savor
<hw>Sa"vor</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Savored</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Savoring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>savorer</ets>, F.
<ets>savourer</ets>. See <er>Savor</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>savour</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
have a particular smell or taste; -- with <xex>of</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To partake of the quality or nature; to indicate the
presence or influence; to smack; -- with <xex>of</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>savors</qex> not much of distraction.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have rejected everything that <qex>savors</qex> of party.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To use the sense of taste.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By sight, hearing, smelling, tasting or <qex>savoring</qex>, and
feeling.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Savor</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Savor
<hw>Sa"vor</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To perceive by the
smell or the taste; hence, to perceive; to note.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To have the flavor or quality of; to indicate the
presence of.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That cuts us off from hope, and <qex>savors</qex> only⟦br⟧
Rancor and pride, impatience and despite.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To taste or smell with pleasure; to delight in; to
relish; to like; to favor.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Savorily</ent>⟦br⟧
